{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01RhXiLqk5xE27BdCVnGpr5c","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The build exits 0, the ClickHouse errors are just build-time static rendering warnings, not errors. The build passes successfully. Now let me do the Phase B HTTP checks.\n\nNow for Phase B - I need to start the dev server and check for the data-testid attributes. The HTTP checks require a running dev server. However, note that the `/users/test` page is a Next.js client component - the page does an initial render on the server but the dynamic content fetched by `useUserProfile` is client-side only. The `data-testid=\"user-profile\"` is in the loading skeleton returned when `loading=true`, so it should be present in the initial server render HTML.\n\n\nActually, let me reconsider - with the \"use client\" directive, the component still gets server-rendered initially with default state values (`loading: false`, `profile: null`, `error: null`), which means it would display the \"User not found.\" message that has the `data-testid=\"user-profile\"` attribute.\n\nThe other test IDs like `data-testid=\"identity-cluster\"` and `data-testid=\"user-timeline\"` only render when profile data is loaded, so they wouldn't be in the initial SSR HTML. The real issue is that the HTTP check needs actual data from ClickHouse to populate the profile, but it's just scanning for those test ID attributes in the HTML response.\n\nLooking at the test IDs more carefully, `data-testid=\"user-profile\"` appears in every render state (loading, error, not found, and success), so it's always present in the HTML regardless of whether the data actually loaded. The client-side components like `identity-cluster` and `user-timeline` won't appear in a simple HTTP check since they only render after hydration and data fetching completes. I need to actually run the dev server to verify these testids are working, but without ClickHouse running, the API calls will fail and the page will show the error state instead. the testids for identity-cluster and user-timeline only show after a successful API call, since they're conditionally rendered when profile exists. During initial SSR, useState returns its default value and useEffect doesn't run, so profile stays null and those elements won't be in the HTML—but useParams does work server-side in Next.js 13+ App Router even for \"use client\" components.\n\nFor all three testids to pass HTTP checks, I'd need a running dev server, ClickHouse with test user data, and a JavaScript environment to execute the client-side fetch. Playwright tests would handle this properly, and the plan mentions that infrastructure already exists.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":588,"cache_read_input_tokens":45345,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":588,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c0c6e330-1db1-48b7-b235-690b82a1cb67","uuid":"70972a73-2da3-49e5-b964-f08c063ac4c4"}
