{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Nw8Jexbt7zboTU6qdhsaWq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the Playwright test pattern. Let me write tests for the F26 user profile page. The key insight is:\n\n1. `data-testid=\"user-profile\"` - always present (even in 404/error states) - can test without ClickHouse\n2. `data-testid=\"identity-cluster\"` - only with profile loaded - needs ClickHouse + seeded data\n3. `data-testid=\"user-timeline\"` - only with profile loaded - needs ClickHouse + seeded data\n   \nMy approach is to write tests that verify the user-profile element renders regardless of state, test the 404 scenario with a non-existent user, and then add tests for the identity-cluster and user-timeline elements that require ClickHouse with seeded data. I also need to keep in mind the HTTP contract checks that verify the presence of data-testid attributes in the responses.\n\nWriting the test file...\n\nI'm realizing there's a potential mismatch: the sprint contract expects HTTP checks to find `data-testid=\"identity-cluster\"` and `data-testid=\"user-timeline\"` in the response, but these elements only render after client-side data fetching completes. Since the page uses `\"use client\"` with useState and useEffect, the initial server render won't include these elements—they only appear once the browser executes the JavaScript and loads the data. A simple HTTP check with curl won't be able to find them because it doesn't execute JavaScript. I need to verify my understanding of how Next.js handles SSR with client components—specifically, `useEffect` doesn't run during server-side rendering, so the data-testids for the identity cluster and timeline won't appear in the initial HTML. Let me actually start the dev server and check the HTTP response to confirm this behavior.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"